	<h2 id="Introduction">Introduction</h2>
	<p style="text-align: justify">
		Rare disorders are defined by an incidence of below 1 in 2000.
		However, due to their sheer number - currently, more than 8000 Mendelian disorders are known
		alone - roughly 3% of the population are affected by a rare disorder.
		the facial gestalt is very informative, sometimes even decisive,
		in the diagnostic process for every second or third patient with a rare disease.
		The performance of next-generation phenotyping (NGP) approaches depends highly on the
		size and diversity of the training dataset. Because collecting a large number of images from
		individuals with rare disorders at a single institution is not feasible, data sharing between
		different sites is crucial, and this is usually done through publication. However, since we are
		re-identifiable by our faces, only about one out of ten patients gives consent. Therefore, we
		propose synthesizing portraits of rare disorders based on real data that can remain local to
		overcome this barrier.
	</p>
	<p>
		The two overall objectives of our project are to enable data sharing
		while maintaining patient privacy and to explain the decisions made by NGP algorithms.
	</p>
	<br>
